title: Seated diners change
caption: Comparison between 2019 (baseline) and subsequent years' number of restaurant seated diners within 18 February, 2020 and 18 January, 2022 in Austin, TX.
insights: Prior to mid-March 2020, daily number of seated diners was nearly same as observed in 2019 followed by a complete 100% drop in seated diners until the start of May, 2020.
By the end of June, 2020, the deviation from the baseline had steeply changed from -100% to about -60% as social distancing orders were relaxed.
For the remainder of 2020, number of seated diners remained at an average of -45.0% below the baseline and the gap has been significantly minimized since early March, 2021.

There is an evident weekly trend in the data where the number of seated diners approaches the baseline as the week progresses so that by the weekend, the difference between the baseline and reporting period is minimized. This trend could be capturing behavior of Austin citizens where they are more likely to visit restaurants later in the week.

Periods surrounding holidays such as 1 September (Labor Day), 27 November (Thanksgiving) and 25 & 31 December (Christmas and New Year) experienced local spikes in number of diners and rose above baseline observations. Interestingly, number of diners around Valentines Day of 2021 (14 February) was significantly lower than the baseline!

It is pertinent to note that the comparison is between each day-of-week of a specific week in the reporting period and corresponding day-of-week in same week in 2019 hence, the dates of local peaks with emphasis on holidays may not be aligned.
